# Return Type Conventions

When writing async functions that can fail:

## Functions that only return success/failure (no data)

Use `Promise<{ error?: Error }>`:

```typescript
const doSomething = async (): Promise<{ error?: Error }> => {
  // On success:
  return {};

  // On failure:
  return { error: new Error('Something went wrong') };
};
```

## Functions that return data or an error

Use `Promise<MutuallyExclusiveResult<T>>` from `@/utils/try-catch`:

```typescript
import { MutuallyExclusiveResult } from '@/utils/try-catch';

const fetchSomething = async (): Promise<
  MutuallyExclusiveResult<{ value: string }>
> => {
  // On success:
  return { data: { value: 'hello' } };

  // On failure:
  return { error: new Error('Failed to fetch') };
};

// Usage:
const { data, error } = await fetchSomething();
if (error) {
  // handle error
  return;
}
// data is guaranteed to exist here
console.log(data.value);
```

This pattern ensures:

- Mutually exclusive results (either data or error, never both)
- Type-safe error handling
- Consistent patterns across the codebase
